document.title: [Archdiocese of Milwaukee Curriculum Documents (Exit Expectations, Gr5)]

9D79B86F86E94382A87D1DF5E048259E.description:
Work collaboratively and respect my
classmates’ ideas, roles, and abilities.

B8833CDF69114FB6ACD2CC5632B62AA6.description:
Demonstrate stewardship inspired by Catholic
values in the care of local and global
environments.

0C6D992B0C9C4884B6098BA36D5A0B97.description:
Communicate information about protecting
Earth’s resources and environment.

143E3816C6734C59AD9D1AF30658A9F5.description:
Combine information about the ways individual
communities protect Earth’s resources.

3428CFDD9D37476F87027E1539D2E1AA.description:
Obtain information about ways individual
communities use science ideas to protect the
Earth’s resources and environment.

84696CFFC6C74FE9B6FA95A6F225C3B1.description:
Human activities in agriculture, industry, and
everyday life have had major effects on the land,
vegetation, streams, ocean, air, and even outer
space. But individuals and communities are doing
things to help protect Earth’s resources and
environments.

14E97337B069419FB3D88755CEF4A210.description:
Obtain and combine information about ways
individual communities use science ideas to protect the
Earth’s resources and environment.

9E1EC583C53A4F80AFCD4246DE4A528A.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth and Human Activity

D08EF1727F55414CBCE4CC4800F745FB.description:
Compare the amount of saltwater to freshwater
on Earth by creating a graph.

AA6798C6DFAF411590AD6089145DCD3D.description:
Identify the different places that water is found
on Earth.

655BDCCB8D7646A6BA60CA5EBCAF8C22.description:
Nearly all of Earth’s available water is in the
ocean.

8A52E0CAC1B84197B02A460710A97549.description:
Describe and graph the amounts and
percentages of water and fresh water in various
reservoirs to provide evidence about the distribution of
water on Earth.

17515E6313A84A76908A026C24934EA8.description: Identify the processes of each major system.

4B2F92D4269544F28DE2FB7020BA19AA.description:
Diagram how two of the four major systems of
Earth work together.

C5C4C06B64AE4B17BEB6BB3BDDEDA0E6.description:
Explain the interconnectedness between two of
the four major systems of Earth (Biosphere,
Hydrosphere, Atmosphere & Geosphere)

A17D9AE275914B98AC3192D3078D9825.description:
Winds and clouds in the atmosphere interact with
the landforms to determine patterns of weather.

FAE7A0FF7AF2462ABE8E3376501469B4.description:
The ocean supports a variety of ecosystems and
organisms, shapes landforms, and influences
climate.

CA7B45681AC542C3B4B9D3B4F63CC114.description:
Earth’s systems interact in multiple ways to affect
Earth’s surface materials and processes.

D2D5BE2B201F4AB6ACF2B9E9A4523F44.description:
Earth’s major systems are the geosphere (solid
and molten rock, soil, and sediments), the
hydrosphere (water and ice), the atmosphere
(air), and the biosphere (living things, including
humans).

DD0E7C268E9D419BA1A9B03EB3665C83.description:
Develop a model using an example to describe
ways the geosphere, biosphere, hydrosphere, and/or
atmosphere interact
[Clarification Statement: Examples could include the
influence of the ocean on ecosystems, landform shape,
and climate; the influence of the atmosphere on
landforms and ecosystems through weather and
climate; and the influence of mountain ranges on wind
and clouds in the atmosphere. The geosphere,
hydrosphere, atmosphere, and biosphere are each
system. ]

20833DD004B24920A5F0AF9091FE5058.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth’s Systems

3A704A8D58CF434DA64BFEB7A2A08C8E.description:
Prepare a graphical representation of the
relationship between the position of Earth with
respect to the sun and the amount of daylight.

156C42D518C1440499EBDF726984CE4E.description:
Identify the relationship between the position
of Earth with respect to the sun and the amount
of daylight.

00FE73DC5C6C4195950893CF7E793E0F.description:
Observe patterns regarding the appearance of
some stars in the night sky.

A1FCEC125E3A4B23B32A596EAC7BE204.description:
Observe patterns in the length of shadows and
the time of day.

290E8C212FA94114A0BE33E4F27FC77A.description:
The orbits of Earth around the sun and of the
moon around Earth, together with the rotation of
Earth about an axis between its North and South
poles, cause observable patterns. These include
day and night; daily changes in the length and
direction of shadows; and different positions of
the sun, moon, and stars at different times of the
day, month, and year.

5D445C326F2C4977AF3EEEF5C0385C4D.description:
Represent data in graphical displays to reveal
patterns of daily changes in length and direction of
shadows, day and night, and the seasonal appearance
of some stars in the night sky.
[Clarification Statement: examples of patterns could
include the position and motion of Earth with respect to
the sun and selected stars that are visible only in
particular months.)

C40C17E5CC9942E4B4B69941CEC333C7.description:
Conclude that objects further away from Earth
appear smaller.

A4B64B84EA7944639C696BAA6B3DFCD0.description:
Conduct an investigation to explore the
relationship between distance and brightness of
an object. (not size)

14132261F4EE4A2099F2826BA5D528E3.description: Stars range greatly in their distance from Earth.

9A0C45EB51CC4AAEBD0D412E232C2549.description:
The sun is a star that appears larger and brighter
than other stars because it is closer.

130A3481CEE9405996E5FC5028E4CDEA.description:
Support an argument that differences in the
apparent brightness of the sun compared to other stars
is due to their relative distances from Earth.

FFEDB24E67DF462C9BDEC16359535573.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth’s Place in the Universe

C53271242AB44F90A152E1AF41C93036.description:
Work collaboratively and respect my
classmates’ ideas, roles, and abilities.

9FF69887A7D94C9DA8DF86A9C69CB5F7.description:
Demonstrate stewardship inspired by
Catholic values in the care of local and global
environments.

16EAC24C23344ED89827F6B8F5FD2A3D.description:
Make a model showing the movement of matter
through different cycles in nature.

0F317B241A9A43F097C1D037B9995E3A.description:
Describe how energy is transferred through an
ecosystem

10C3F81B91BD4BDCACD9B0BD8004D617.description:
Organisms are related in food chains and food
webs

7FA7671BBAAE4FE4BF3DFBFE40BAD222.description:
Food of almost any kind of animal can be traced
back to plants

14E2A410F3B24CBB8C673E4B7B2302EA.description:
Develop a model to describe the movement
of matter among plants, animals, decomposers, and
the environment.
[Clarification Statement: Emphasis is on the idea that
matter that is not food (air, water, decomposed
materials in soil) is changed by plants into matter that
is food. Examples of systems could include organisms,
ecosystems, and the Earth.)

7F6B8FBAEB4B4EB0905974217FD3DACA.description: LIFE SCIENCES: Ecosystems: Interactions, Energy, and Dynamics

B2FB7733EB5C462EBB6DA1DE9877561A.description:
Provide evidence that plants acquire their
materials for growth from water and air.

2757ED6BCD6642588E5C7B4D3246771C.description:
Design an investigation to test which materials
plants need for growth.

69877280CF4743B2B7A546DDE49362A9.description: Explain the process of seed development.

2366DA0F4E52410BA2D4D2F95028F2DE.description:
Plants acquire their material for growth chiefly from
water and air

BED04C31EC934447ACF209DC074C1C53.description:
Support an argument that plants get the
materials they need for growth chiefly from air and
water.
[Clarification Statement: Emphasis is on the idea that
plant matter comes mostly from air and water, not
from the soil]

25133FE2EFF84ED59A61F0584D025669.description: LIFE SCIENCES: From Molecules to Organisms: Structures and Processes

B5D159699CEF44578E18037669B4A77D.description: Work collaboratively and respect my classmates’ ideas, roles, and abilities.

7FA04E2D86B0441383ABF316AF901C0F.description:
Identify that animals use food for body repair, growth,
motion, and to maintain body warmth.

1E6C5B5B8FA648C4B29D27D91483DDAC.description:
Create a model to show the movement of energy from
the sun, to plants, to animals.

AF7CF295DE2D4D4A8F64F94201E81FA2.description:
Food provides animals with the materials
they need for body repair and growth and
the energy they need to maintain body
warmth and for motion.

923A962AC3C1442DB9BE21C63DF866FB.description:
Plants capture energy from the sun to
produce their own food.

EE892DF0B92F4B5FA5F162F0C7687710.description:
The energy released [from] food was once
energy from the sun that was captured by
plants in the chemical process that forms
plant matter (from air and water).

4CAD6D67DA094F1689F8A1B45B352515.description:
Use models to describe that energy in
animals’ food (used for body repair, growth, motion,
and to maintain body warmth) was once energy from
the sun.
[Clarification Statement: examples of models could
include diagrams and flowcharts.]

2832E03B1B494DF0A20B7007BE0AB7E6.description:
Argue that the force exerted by Earth on an object is
directed down.

CC3A6485EA174B1B92104AD6BF75C9BD.description:
Provide evidence that Earth’s gravity pulls objects
down.

3B6D3AA7AB91405CA29DDC24C36056F7.description:
Identify the relationship between the strength of a
force and its effect on an object.

44DDE9E5F20C4DC29D140CD59CD2417C.description:
The gravitational force of Earth acting on
an object near Earth’s surface pulls that
object toward the planet’s center.

74E0A9B1D9AC462DB1F569DBC4DDF971.description:
Support an argument that the gravitational
force exerted by Earth on objects is directed down.
[Clarification Statement: “Down” is a local description
of the direction that points toward the center of the spherical Earth. Assessment does not include
mathematical representation of gravitational force.]

E62222F3402C454EBA13147610610452.description: PHYSICAL SCIENCE: Motion and Stability: Forces and Interactions

18347DBC5FD64A4EA1E880C33C6436FB.description:
Investigate to tell whether the mixing of two or more
substances results in the new substances.

F3C96F61632045F8A42AB6CB48AE84FE.description:
When two or more different substances
are mixed, a new substance with different
properties may be formed.

520B2B8EC9224D3A9089CE5CF0D4810E.description:
Conduct an investigation to determine
whether the mixing of two or more substances
results in new substances.

F8A0A1312EF644C1B9711AE62F9750BD.description: Distinguish materials based on their properties.

E9461F12AC8749E7B7ADBBF89B7EAF3C.description:
Measurements of a variety of properties
can be used to identify materials.

554F8EEAB0064F9399D2C24A56B92A8B.description:
Make observations and measurements to
identify materials based on their properties
[Clarification Statement: examples of materials to be
identified could include baking soda and other
powders, metals, minerals, and liquids. Examples of
properties could include color, hardness, reflectivity,
electrical conductivity, thermal conductivity,
response to magnetic forces, and solubility. Density is
not intended as an identifiable property. Assessment
does not include density or distinguishing mass and
weight]

F89B8221BF5B4ED0A8E4F583C087B028.description:
Conclude that a substance's weight remains the same
after a change.

4CA6F9BFED6B419F8C8AE88E5B9E65B0.description:
Measure a substance's weight before and after a
change.

92184306938B4D1FB752322F55D84EE6.description:
Identify a change occurred from heating, cooling, and
mixing of substances.

784F9D1904944674ABADD1687B309C13.description:
Regardless of the reaction or change in
properties of a substance, the total weight
does not change.

B5BAA745FAAC4997B1C82AE00E63B802.description:
Substances can go through changes such
as heating, cooling, and being mixed.

8B1CDC32F4524FC89DBAF810B78733D4.description:
Measure and graph quantities to provide
evidence that regardless of the type of change that
occurs when heating, cooling, or mixing substances,
the total weight of matter is conserved.
[Examples of reactions to changes could include
phase changes, dissolving, and mixing to form new
substances. Assessment Boundary: does not include
distinguishing mass and weight.]

0D350A1A6A534D8E9E9942C86E5538FF.description:
Identify through an experiment that molecules are
present.

8FF6E39D06184005B42C89CC0ED7932F.description:
Develop a model to demonstrate that matter is made of
particles too small to be seen.

F3DEAA8009794276B08DB889D3C388E1.description:
Models can be used to show particles and
explain their behavior.

F83A314246C94F72AC3CF2E1E108CCD0.description:
Matter of any type can be subdivided into
particles that are too small to see

5A5AA126B7B7482BB636CF7C3ACCF6A7.description:
Develop a model to describe that matter is
made of particles too small to be seen.
[Examples of evidence could include adding air to
expand a basketball, compressing air in a syringe,
dissolving sugar in water, and evaporating salt water.
Assessment Boundary: assessment does not include
the atomic scale mechanism of evaporation and
condensation, or defining unseen particles. ]

148BF84D94FB4DA88F433E8737373F7B.description: PHYSICAL SCIENCE: Matter and Its Interactions
